Quite possibly the worst dining experience I've ever had. From the lukewarm reception to the lacklustre courses, one struggles to find the slightest semblance of a redeeming quality for this "priceless jewel", as dubbed by the powers that be behind the Michelin guide.

In fact, its presence on the roster calls all other entries into contention, notwithstanding that our visits elsewhere were delightful, and this being the chief (and sole) offender.

There are many outfits which are pretentious, but they at least have the decency to match their air of superiority with an impressive gastronomic experience.

Odette was neither.

(1) Service & Ambience
We were seated in the main dining hall. If you prefer a modicum of privacy while you try to make justifications for this sorry excuse of a meal, well, unfortunately, you would be fresh out of luck.

When we were not making awkward eye contact with patrons seated across from us, we were treated to an incessant, unrefined flurry of staff who simply could not remain out of sight. To top it off, we had the great fortune to be seated where the entire kitchen could gawk at us throughout the meal while the ‚Äúopen kitchen‚Äù barely provided vision of kitchen activity.

The entire atmosphere was distracting, intrusive and highly uncomfortable.

(2) Presentation
Plating was boring, the very limited finesse present was contrived, and there was a severe lack of performative entrances.

(3) Culinary
- Grignotages: Flavours were very muted. Nothing spectacular.
- Mushroom ‚ÄúTea‚Äù and Brioche: Appetising and earthy. Quite possibly the best dish Odette has to offer.
- Normandy Brown Crab: A complete blank. Zero flavour and there was hardly any crab.
- Rosemary Smoked Organic Egg: Laughable. For all its fanfare, it tasted barely a notch above a soft-boiled egg made at home.
- Langoustine ‚ÄòComme un Dumpling‚Äô: Supplement $98, but hold the flavour. Truffles were either not properly stored or of a low quality, as they had no aroma at all. Langoustine was tasteless.
- Seaweed Butter Poached Scallop: Decent presentation and flavours, but I am being generous here. Very forgettable.
- Aveyron Lamb Saddle: A very sad lamb dish. The texture was completely off (tough, wrong mouthfeel), and its flavour was overly gamey with no depth.
- ‚ÄòIspahan‚Äô Vacherin: A tribute to‚Ä¶ sad ice cream and sickeningly sweet artificial rose syrup? When I thought it could not get any worse, the server cleared our relatively untouched plates without bothering to ask how we found the dish. Come on.
- Douceurs: Looked sad, and tasted like it looked. Canel√©s were way too hard with barely any flavour, and seriously, cut fruits? Regardless of provenance, such a selection betrays laziness and incompetence.

(4) Value
No uni. No caviar. No foie gras. No high quality ingredients. Did I just pay a premium to be ogled at while I eat unimpressive and unimaginative food?

I am in no way saying those are obligatory inclusions, but when you can offer nothing else, at least soften the blow.

They say ‚Äúprice is what you pay, value is what you get‚Äù. Well, at Odette, the price is a four-figure sum, and the value is an inside joke "at least it's better than Odette", that I can make reference to every single time I have a substandard meal.

Pathetic.

##

I will not even deign to discuss elements such as complexity and synergy, as the individual flavours (or lack thereof) were either too muted or completely missed the mark.

In summary, dining at Odette was a lesson in mediocrity.

The food did not even taste bad, which makes it worse ‚Äì because what that means is, it's not that Odette isn't trying, or that the crew has no formal training. Odette is pulling out all the stops, only to arrive at this utterly forgettable and pedestrian experience. Disappointing and embarrassing.

text:
My visit to this restaurant was deeply disappointing. The moment I walked in, I noticed how unclean the place was, which set the tone for the rest of the experience. The entire atmosphere was moody and unpleasant, and it felt like the establishment hadn‚Äôt been maintained in years.

To make matters worse, there was only one washroom available which was behind a curtain(!), and it was in horrible condition‚Äîdark, dirty, and clearly outdated. It was honestly shocking to see a restaurant neglect such basic hygiene.

The food was equally bad, lacking quality, and the drink selection was abysmal. They didn‚Äôt even have enough inventory to support their menu, with just a few half-empty bottles on hand. It was clear they weren‚Äôt prepared to serve their customers properly.

As you can refer to the order receipt of the dishes, this is a takeaway order. I personally ordered at the eatery yesterday (while braving with a heavy wet weather hoping to have a good meal) here comes my review.  The prawn briyani, a total disappointment in terms of taste. The prawns are not fresh at all so its a very stale taste while eating and basmati rice is overcooked.  Being a briyani lover I have tasted briyani in many shops around Singapore, from regular hawkers, to authentic Indian Muslim briyanis and also even established restaurants and this is one of the poorly prepared Briyani and Tandoori Briyani is also tasteless.

As for the fish curry. The eatery uses Ikan Tenggiri (local Malay word) also known as Spanish mackerels and I ask for the tail portion. The fish has a mushy texture when break into pieces to eat and tastes sour. Likely the fish maybe going bad soon. Fish curry is a very basic dish for any non-vegetarian Indian eateries, a base curry to use for rice, pratas and etc and even the Fish curry in this shop cannot even make it to 1 star. If the dishes are superb, spending more money for good food is worth it and I strongly believe its okay to pay for good food. This is a overly priced neighbourhood shop at Bukit Batok for a badly cooked briyani and curry fish.  Even didn't provide poppadoms for briyani. I think the only item that taste nice is the Raita (cucumber, carrot and green chillies with yogurt). Being a local Indian, I know how authentic Indian dishes should taste. Compared to smaller eateries at Little India or even in at hawker stalls, I have tasted better Indian cuisine.  This shop seriously has to polish up their culinary skills. For heaven's sake STOP using MSG in all your food.

Absolutely Awful Experience at Nalan, Singapore ‚Äì Never Going Back

I took my family to Nalan for dinner, and it turned out to be a huge mistake. The service was absolutely pathetic. We ordered a simple tomato soup and veg fried rice. The soup took 15-20 minutes to arrive, which was fine ‚Äî but after that, it felt like they completely forgot our table.

The waiter cleared the soup bowls but gave only two plates for a table of three. I had to ask again just to get one more plate for my father ‚Äî basic common sense seemed completely absent.

Then came the worst part ‚Äî we waited an entire hour for the veg fried rice. Tables that arrived after us were being served, while we kept waiting. We asked the staff politely about our order, and all we got was a robotic ‚Äúit‚Äôs coming.‚Äù Another 30 minutes passed, and still nothing. We finally lost our patience, paid for the soup, and left ‚Äî hungry and frustrated. Not a single apology from the staff for the insane delay.

To top it all off, the prices are ridiculously expensive for the kind of service and average food they offer. Absolutely zero value for money. This place does not care about customer experience.

If you‚Äôre looking for a peaceful dinner with decent service, stay far away from Nalan. Never coming back.

text: Chicken rice was fragrant! Chilli sauce is fresh and has the right amount of spiciness and garlic. But the main problem is the chicken. It is tough and the chef we got smashed the bones to smithereens, leaving bone fragments in almost every piece of chicken. This is how people crack their teeth! Its my second visit here, I feel the "cooked" food quality not really great. Their beef come with sukiyaki has a strong smell, and the fire of the hotpot was so weak, it took a long time to cook. I also order tokatsu set in previous visit, the pork cutlet was overly fried and served in mild hot, its hard to chew, seems not freshly prepared. I had the same Tokatsu set meal in Ichiban Amk Hub before, which is so much tastier. Service from staff at this branch also need to be improved. The tray used to serve the food was wet, and staff won't take the initiative to provide bowl which need to use to consume sukiyaki, the previous they didn't give me chopsticks, soya sauce & wasabi for sashimi.

Best chicken rice but terrible experience queuing for it. They allow their regulars to cut queue which makes the people queuing look like idiots.

If you are a regular of this shop, please stop cutting queue. You are making everyone's life terrible.

Had communication issues with the front counter as one of them had very thick accent. I bought the Mandi chicken and half of the chicken was quite dry. Even though it was half a chicken but the portion was quite small. The rice was dry too. Giving 2 stars because the rice portion was generous.

I don‚Äôt understand how the reviews claim that the mala is cheap or affordable. Not sure if I was overcharged by accident, my meal was $25 including rice and take away. Mala itself was $23, rice was $1.50 and take away was $0.50. I saw the ‚Ä¶

All said, the experience is pleasant just because of an excellent staff. Well done, Catherine!

business_name: Morsels Restaurant & Gastro Wine Bar | Morsels Private Dining
text:
The reservation system and service at this restaurant need improvement. I arrived for lunch before another couple but was seated after them, despite both parties ordering the same lunch set and the fact that lunch service ends at 3 pm. The server did not explain why the other couple was seated first until I asked. This left a negative impression, especially since I had made an effort to arrive on time, even taking a cab to meet the reservation. I was frustrated, and the server acknowledged this by offering complimentary wine.

On a positive note, the food was decent, though the portions were slightly small, and the pork belly was dry.

However, the restaurant's small space made it feel cramped, and there were a few instances of people bumping into the chair as they walked past. Additionally, I agree with another reviewer regarding the hygiene and cleanliness. The utensils were placed on the table, and I did not feel comfortable using them.
Taste is alright, but hygiene is bad. Tables were oily and flies were swarming the whole time I was eating.
2 weeks ago

business_name: Trattoria da Mimmo Restaurant and Pizzeria
text:
I didn't enjoy the food due to the quality of food served. It was also pricey for a restaurant in a residential area.

It was frustrating to see that other customers who arrived later and sat in more visible areas were attended to first. After waiting for about 10-15 minutes, I decided to walk to the cashier to place our order. The staff then told me to sit down, and they would come over.

We ordered additional food after our meal was served, but it took a very long time to come. When we asked the staff about the status, he said he would check but he never returned with an update. We only found out the order hadn't even been prepared when we chose to cancel it and settle the bill. The entire experience was incredibly disappointing and fell below expectations.

They have quite a number of local cuisine on the menu and the food is actually not bad. However, the service is bad considered that the location (+price) is considered upper stream. We went in at lunch time and it was not crowded. Quickly placed our orders and chat along. 20mins later, more and more customers came in and filled the other tables.

While we were enjoying our chat and noticed that it has passed 30mins of waiting, the table of 5 beside who came much later had their food served. I checked with the staff and she said she will check, but I looked at her and she never even gone to the kitchen. 10mins later I asked the same staff again and she said she will check. She never get back at all. Next, we see 2 other tables being served their food, I checked with another staff and he did not even respond a single word? Then I asked the 3rd staff who then went into kitchen to check, and said the food is coming. By then, we were almost 1 hour into the wait. Finally the food came and we rushed our meal for our next appointment. I feedback to the "captain" of the restaurant while at the cashier, he mentioned that they are short of staff, but that does not answer the part of why 4 other tables got served first. He just kept quiet and did not even let me check the bill before deduction. Poor service attitude.

1 hour wait is ridiculous and no explanation on why other tables were served first, not even a word of apology too. Much has to be improved on the service. The atmosphere and food is okay but this service is just chasing people away.

Think of this as a lite version of Canopy at HortPark, with fewer menu options, a much smaller alfresco area, and little shelter from the elements.

The location is far from ideal. The nearest car park is perpetually full on weekends and public holidays, forcing you to battle aggressive drivers for a spot or settle for a multi-storey HDB car park at least ten minutes away, where available lots start from level five.

Visually, the caf√© is striking, blending modern aesthetics amidst the surrounding Chinese architecture. Its elevated position makes it pleasantly windy, a point to note for pet owners who are limited to the tiny alfresco area despite the spacious indoor seating.

Service is hit-or-miss, depending on the staff. We were initially welcomed by an attentive gentleman who did his best to seat us comfortably, even with a faulty overhead fan. However, the experience quickly unraveled when a female server repeatedly mixed up orders between tables, offered no explanation, and walked off awkwardly, leaving us confused.

The menu is uninspiring, with better options limited to brunch dishes or deep-fried staples like fish and chips. While portions are reasonable for the price, the food tasted disappointingly frozen rather than fresh.

Unless you are making a quick pit stop after a walk in the park, your money is better spent elsewhere.

We ordered the truffle cream pasta, drawn in by the promise of tortellini. The sauce was delicious, but the white button mushrooms overwhelmed the truffle‚Äôs subtle flavor, which was disappointing. To our surprise, we were served ravioli instead of the advertised tortellini. The ravioli didn‚Äôt pair well with the sauce; tagliatelle would have been a better match to carry the dish.
Given the steep price, we expected a standout experience, but it fell short. After eating, we were still hungry yet lacked the desire to order more. Overall, the meal didn‚Äôt live up to the cost or our expectations.

Also, I think the bowl is kind of shallow and difficult to eat from

business_name: Signature Restaurant & Bar - Best Briyani and Grill chicken
text:
TLDR: food is alright, waiting time is a horrible gamble.
my friends and i sat down at 6:30pm with barely anyone around, we had high hopes because of the reviews too but turned out our food firstly had a 30-45mins wait with a huge gap in between. we wanted to save our naans for the last dish but it took another 45 mins to come and it seemed like they completely forgot the order üò¢ we also ordered drinks and they came super slowly, my friend ordered a ice lemon tea and after an hr and a half, we reminded them and they came out with a canned lemon tea üò≠üòÇ at this point we were not even surprised and just wanted to pay and leave to eat somewhere else. would have appreciated if they forgot the order to come back and check with us again...

Really wanted to like this place as the restaurant was set in such a beautiful environment on top of a hill with lovely surroundings in a school. But the food really needed more attention. Ordered the fish and chips set. Granted that it was a steal that at $16.50, there was mushroom soup and bread, main course, dessert and a hot tea. The breadroll was nice, but the soup has more flour than mushroom. The main was beautifully presented and I was really happy to dive into the food. But The fish was undercooked and batter was still wet and slimy inside, the chips was hard and not crispy. Feels almost that the the food was cooked at too low a temperature. The side salad that came with it was a really weird tasting dressing like a mushroom vinaigrette gone wrong.
Lastly the dessert consisting of a cube of marble cake and brownie with ice cream tasted floury and dry.
Kudos that the staff re cooked a new fish and chips for me. But it still tasted off with the fish too oily and still slimy and the chips still hard not and crispy.
Hope the kitchen will see  this review positively and make some improvements. Hope to go back one day to have a good meal with student waiters that were more knowledgeable about the menu as well.

business_name: Shan Cheng (Ipoh Delicacies) ‚óè Â±±Âüé - Bukit Panjang Plaza
text: We wanted to try Ipoh Hor Fun and this seems to be the only option around Bukit Panjang. We ordered 3 different styles of Hor Fun and Noodles for a broader perspective of this restaurant. Our collective conclusion is this restaurant is not worth the visit until improvements are made. The Hor Fun Soup tasted bland and diluted. The Hor Fun Dry comes with a separate bowl of soup and that is also diluted. For relative comparison, the noodle dishes here are average food court standard but at a premium price. As for the service, I'd expect a restaurant (this is not a food court) selling at a higher price to offer better customer service. As we walked in and asked for a table, the staff directed us backward to the entrance pointing to a pile of menus and telling us to come back to the counter for our order. No, they're not rude, just want to point out this is not a service-oriented restaurant. They could have continued with the flow to have us seated, brought along the menus, and then explained their ordering process. There were 4 staff total and we were the only table on a Monday at 5pm! No excuse for being too busy for better customer service. Food is ordered in person over the counter, paid on the spot (credit card accepted) and a device is provided that will buzz when our order is ready for pickup. When I asked (not demanding) for tissue, their reply was we don't offer tissues in a tone and expression that made me feel like I was asking a silly question. ü§¶‚Äç‚ôÇÔ∏è Other than a clean dining area, can't think of other positives to recommend this restaurant.

Disappointed with the customer service. The staff did not clearly inform us that the olive rice would take 15 minutes to prepare, even though our other dishes were already being served. This caused an unnecessary delay and disrupted our meal.

When we were making payment, the cashier, Catherine, was confirming our order and we were taking a moment to review. Out of nowhere, she asked, ‚ÄúDo you understand Chinese?‚Äù ‚Äî which came across as rude and uncalled for. Such a question was unnecessary and left a bad impression.

The experience was rather disappointing as the food in general fell way below expectation. Felt that most food was too creamy and heavy. Lobster was undercooked, and half the dishes were a tad too salty. I couldn't finish most of my dishes. My fav was the tomato confit at the start. Service was amazing though. Just wished the food was better for a 3 Michelin star restaurant. Compared to other restaurants of the same calibre like Odette and Zen, definitely need more improvement in the design of menu

Surprisingly, despite its location adjacent to a caf√©, one might not initially perceive it as a fine dining restaurant which exclusively serves only set course menus.

Plating: The plating for the carbonara is pretty bad given that its $20++. Using a metal plate that is probably used in a canteen. When i try to peel my chicken wing it doesnt stabilize on the table, the plate will spin as i peel.

Waiting time was alittle long for the fact that there was only 3 tables occupied when im there. Food was out in about 30 mins?

Conclusion, the food isnt that value for dollar. The best way to conclude is that the food are worth 15% lesser than it is priced.

text: Ambience on a Friday afternoon is surprising nice. Dishes were as expected. The only thing is the beef rib was a tad too tough‚Ä¶ the endive salad with mozzarella and oysters made up for it

First time trying this korean street dining restaurant, but was a bit disappointed with the service. I ordered my food at 1:10pm, most of the tables were served, maybe left 1 or 2 tables of guests waiting for their food. They served me my drink and then 6 pieces chicken, but my main dish was taking forever. I have to even pace my chicken wings so I won't finish them before my main fish come. I was having my last piece of chicken at 1:33, finally 1:35 my noodles came. While i was waiting i googled jjapagetti because i have never tried before - "also known as Chapagetti, is a popular Korean instant noodle dish made by Nongshim, known for its black bean sauce flavor. It's the second most popular ramyeon (ramen) in South Korea and was the first instant noodle product to resemble the Chinese dish jjajangmyeon." - according to google. Wow, it is an instant noodle product but it took close to half hour to cook! While having my 2nd last piece of chicken i still saw the kitchen chefs walking around, they didn't have anything else to cook i wondered. It was only then one of the 2 staff came and check my order - 11-1:30pm, the restaurant not even half full but they only have 2 staff + 1 manager, clearly they still lack of manpower. The staff didn't apologize for missing my order or whatsoever. Last part, the noodles was warm, but the ham and egg are cold. üòí im not angry, im upset and disappointed.
Edit: i just made payment and reflected to the manager, she was chasing for another table's order too. So apparently the kitchen was taking their time to cook the food, and the staff might be new they didn't dare to chase the kitchen for orders. The manager apologized, but still. Hope the kitchen system can be better.

the food standard has dropped. the striploin steak and baked potato was still rather yummy, but the spaghetti was not very tasty. just salty.

the service was quite unsettling. we went at 1pm on a thursday, so it was not very packed. the waiters were still rushing about, so we were ignored a few times as they walked around in a huff. my mum asked for milk and sugar for coffee and the waitress pointed out the sugar on the table. my mum said thank you, can i get the milk? and she strode off without saying anything. i understand that FnB is sometimes hectic and I've been a service staff before, but there no need to be like that.

i think there were only 3 staff servicing 5-6 tables. can be improved

Had dinner here, we spent 20$ for 4 of us.
I usually don‚Äôt give a ‚Äú3 star or less‚Äù review unless there‚Äôs something terribly wrong with the food.
Firstly, the Gobi manchurian smelled so bad. We took one piece each and threw away the rest.
Secondly, we felt dehydrated right after eating, so much so that we were up in the bed for the next 3h.
Plus we started burping. And felt acid reflux . There‚Äôs something in the vada, dosa and idly batter (may be too much soda??) !
There‚Äôs so much wind in our bodies, it took 2 cups of warm tea to settle down and finally sleep in peace.
Finally, I won‚Äôt recommend eating here. Price is very good. Comparable to other shops in the hawker center. But, it‚Äôs not worth our health. So not going back again!
Hope they improve their quality at least a bit to not cause these health issues to people who eat here.

text: Food was generally ok, soy sauce chicken was tough, London roast duck was good, beef with fish porridge arrived without fish. Service was unpolished. Great place to bring dogs though.

business_name: Dim Sum Express (Kuai Can Dian Xin)
text:
Basic and acceptable dim sum when it comes to taste, but extremely value for money. $1.30 dim sum will definitely fill you up and breaks the mental barrier that dim sum is expensive.

Taste is generally average for the 5 items i ordered as shown in pics attached to review. But hey, when that volume of food amounts to $6.50.... how to complain right?

The adjacent drink stall also serves up pretty decent beverages.
a year ago

The location is walkable distance from jem mall. This place offers a delightful range of South Indian and North Indian dishes that are good. The taste is just ok. Do not expect much. Briyani quantity is normal. The pricing is reasonable. Definitely a good place for evening tea. Can see office goers coming to this place for evening snacks and tea.
Their hummus is of standard, but one could say that is something expected of an establishment that brands itself as the go-to for Mediterranean food. ‚Ä¶
Wanted to try mee goreng but I order the wrong one as Thai style instead of mamak style ‚Ä¶

Had their tasting menu.  Service was great.  They sat us outside even though the whole restaurant was empty.  Waiter said the outside was better as it isn‚Äôt as loud.  Think it was BS.  The tasting menu was a little too much food.  I don‚Äôt know how people eat ao much.  The guava was an interesting starter, not part of the tasting.  Suckling pig wasn‚Äôt crispy.  Peking duck wasn‚Äôt that great.  The prawn was good.  The soup was excellent. Abalone was ok. Fish was amazing.  Lobster noodles was good. Dessert was bla.  We also tried to get in for dim sum and they said needed to be booked 5 days in advanced.  Such snobby hosts.  Would have wanted to try their dim sum.  But after a mediocre tasting, wouldn‚Äôt want to waste my money on trying their lunch.

Mushroom soup was creamy and did not taste like it's from a can. Bread was fresh and crispy.

Tempura squid was freshly fried, though could have had more batter. Also slightly oily and could have been more thoroughly drained. Nicely seasoned.

Steak was cooked and seasoned well, but was smaller than expected. Bone seemed deep fried and was tasty. However, not very worth the price point at 108$ for the steak.
so it's obvious that the draw is the food. delicious. not value for money. our smeagol pizza cost $40 (May 2025) but it was very yummy. the bread was pillow-ey so it's a treat for the mouth. ‚Ä¶

üíß Water is complimentary & and self-service.

Price range starts from $6-$13 for mains for an aglio olio, which is pretty okay-ish for price. We wanted to order the lunch set deals, but the online product listing kept switching on and off? I'm not sure if it's a bug glitch because we can't order the pasta set either, when the hot plate set was the only one off. Yet when we checked with the staff again, the hot plate was back on, but the pasta was not. A lot of the items were also out of stock during lunch hour as well. We kinda gave up figuring it out and just ordered ala carte pasta.

üç§ Basil Prawn Pasta did not look like the photos, but it was still not bad. It leans towards the cream sauce with basil style with 4 shrimps & 2 salad leaves. Portion size is small, and the handmade pasta had a texture closer to korean ramyun, which was.. interesting.
I rate: 3/5 üåü

ü¶ê Seafood Tom Yum Pasta was pretty okay as well. Sauce has a prominent sour tang of a tom Yum Soup, as ingredients consisted of shrimps, clams, and scallops. Pasta like the above was chewy and wavy like korean ramyun.
I rate: 3/5 üåü

Expensive

business_name: Morsels Restaurant & Gastro Wine Bar | Morsels Private Dining
text: Absolutely delighted by the "Asian noodles of the week" (their take on Asam laksa). One could taste the depth of the flavourful smoky broth and the freshness of the seafood. I will be back for the wanton mee. Unfortunately, I can't say the same about the appetizers & beef ragu pasta. Rather one dimensional with a dominant flavour with little to no elements of surprise. Floor service was great. Prices are on the higher side (hey, it's Dempsey after all) but the Asian noodles are really worth revisiting.
Overrated

Came with my walking group after exploring the newly re-opened Chinese Garden.  The restaurant is a nice place with tasteful decorations. Pity we could not see the external garden surroundings during the night.

The food was reasonably well cooked, although a bit pricy. There was no pizza available when we visited. The seared sea bass was tender and quite fresh, although in my opinion the source was a bit too cheesy and lacking zest and taste.  My dining companions gave good feedback to the roasted chicken thighs they had ordered, and enjoyed their meal. The fish and chips was very generous in quantity.

The service was pretty good and the staff very friendly.

Came here to check out the place on a late monday afternoon after knowing that a friend works at the nearby ships in the pier about 2-3 pm, wasn‚Äôt greeted by any staff and had to take my own menu. Realised afterwards that the staff were having their lunch but still didn‚Äôt feel welcomed. And to top it off, an indian waitstaff, not sure of her name, served my dessert to me after i was done with my main and just gave a glare at me without saying anything. Like honestly, not sure why im paying service charge even for such poor service and attitude. And you guys should really retrain your staff, especially that indian waitstaff. People come here to dine and enjoy their day, not to feel uncomfortable by the attitude coming from your staff. Atmosphere and the food is the only thing thats good about this place.

We had pineapple fried rice, prawn cakes and boat noodles. Boat noodles were good but portion too small for $1. Would love the soup to be piping hot instead of lukewarm. Other dishes were normal, have had better ones at other local Thai restaurant.

business_name: Signature Restaurant & Bar - Best Briyani and Grill chicken
text: Food was okay. This was my go to restaurant for yummy food 6 months ago. Today i went after a gap of 6 months I think the chef got changed or management not sure though. Food was not so great as it used to be. We actually had a party order in Jan 2023 from the ‚Äúsignature ‚Äú food was so good then. I was totally disappointed with food today.

The best I tried was their Queso Fundido, broiled Oaxaca cheese fondue, crumbled chorizo, serrano that was served with corn tortilla chips. And another plus is that they have Jarritos cola as I really like it.
The things that didn‚Äôt impress me was their Quesadillas, either pork or chicken did it for any of us by the table. Unfortunately the  same goes for the Tacos. They all had sone strange taste.
The interior and vibe is nice here, and they could do so much with the place, I hope they do but I will wait until I come back. But I will, as I believe in second chances.

The menu was badly designed, there is no picture for every dish and there is no indication of spiciness beside the dish.
The creamy fried mushroom was too sweet. ‚Ä¶
Warm, attentive service. Non-experimental French cooking with luxurious touches at an elevated price point, a bit too restrained for my liking.

Healthy meals but it's expensive. If you order their oat rice and you would like to add on extra dishes, few pieces of long bean will charged you 0.50 $. Very little portion of dishes add on with extra 0.50$. Not worth. Don't add on anything for value meal.

business_name: Yi Jia Le Wah Chye Seafood Restaurant
text:
My childhood place to dine in with my family since we live nearby mostly for dinner when we are tired to cook and dine in here for dinner

Just posting a review to contribute a bit

It's not bad. I used to visit this stall when I was in my teens and living in the west. It's still good but somehow the top up soup was tastier than that that came with the ribs. Flavours are good but from memory the flavours were richer then.

Duck ragu pasta was al dente and had nice chunks of duck meat. Pizza subsequently took 35 mins to come after we finished the pasta, don‚Äôt know why the wait was so long. Pizza crust was nice and crispy. Would not recommend the ?Blueberry almond tart as the almond taste is very artificial and blueberries were not fresh, Cake very dense. They wrote happy birthday on the plate and took a polaroid for us so +1 star.

Revisited this place on a Friday evening between 845-930. The place was very crowded  but was severely understaffed. Only 2 staff on rotation, one cooking while one washing dishes or taking orders, all the while customers keep streaming in. ‚Ä¶

3 star based on buffet menu value.
(Non-seafood night, Sunday)

If you are here for buffet menu value, you will be disappointed.

The seafood section serves snow crab, prawns, mussels, clams. Oysters are not an option, at least on Sunday when I patronized. You might be able to find it on seafood night.

Chili crab was not available as well. The closest you can get to chili crab is the mantou accompanied by the chili crab sauce beside it. If you are adventurous, the fried soft shell crab combined with chili crab sauce might satisfy your chili crab craving. All that oil in the fried soft shell crab will make you feel jelat quickly.

There is basic selection of sashimi and nigiri, I find the lack of premium cut like Mekajiki (Swordfish) disappointing.

There are live stations serving local and international food like laksa, chicken rice, roasted meat. The dessert selection was great, there was a wide selection of confectionery. Those with  sweet tooth will be thrilled.

I find that there is a great selection of cheese and cold cut meat, the best out of the buffets I‚Äôve been to so far.

The atmosphere is excellent and your date will certainly be impressed by the decor, furnishing and service.

Each portion of their noodles is huge, probably can be shared for 1.5 - 2 pax. The price is slightly high but its justifiable since the portion is huge. However, their food lacks flavour. The chicken winglets were average. Their ingredients were very averagey as well. This restaurant had a great concept and potential but was unfortunately a flop. Not interested in visiting them again.
Ordered the braised beef noodle, pork chop egg fried rice, steamed pork dumplings (xiao long pao), and vegetable pork dumplings. ‚Ä¶

Food was delicious and well-executed (the dessert, mackerel and truffle emulsion were the best out of our 4-course meal) but the lack of care in service killed it for me. Cold, inattentive service from the minute we walked in. Treated as ‚ÄúAmerican tourists‚Äù (we are not) with second class service. All 4 other tables (mostly business and a honeymooner) were touched by Chef and we were only spoken as he got the door for us as we had to walk up and pay our bill (all other tables the check was brought to). No napkin service, water glasses left nearly empty for my partner, table was not pulled out for her, asking me for my allergies although it was indicated on the reservation - all of which are fairly standard for service, albeit for non-Michelin rated restaurants.

As a 20+ year veteran in the hospitality and luxury travel industry, I was very disappointed and appalled at this service. Was it the way we were dressed, in summer clothing because it was our last day sightseeing in Singapore? Because I only wanted one glass of wine with my lunch? There were many opportunities to turn the experience around at many points during service. The only saving grace was the female server who was able to pick up queues and answer my curiosities about the food and cooking techniques so thank you to her.

first time to try since queue is just starting to build up, because I am very hungry I ate it right away while waiting for my bubble tea next door. the taste is good but the kebab was barely warm at all, I thought the toaster would be really hot since the staff only put it in there like 3-4 seconds and wrap it quickly, would have been a good experience eating a hot food.

A halal tze char place serving up the usual dishes. We came on a weekday and it was full so we had to sit outside. We could also see many people ordering takeaway dishes too. We tried the following dishes: ‚Ä¶

My family of 5 had brunch at Penang Island Cafe. The soya bean at S$2 for a tall glass was freshly made and fragrant. The curry for the pork skin curry cheong fun was rich so was the chilli for the noodle sets. Portion of the nasi lemak was too large for my elderly mum to finish. My family was full of praises for the meat served. They were crispy and flavourful. We spent a total of ~S$44 on 20 Dec 2024. The cafe has aircon and open air seating.

Dropped by Nalan at Serangoon for lunch, excited to try their South Indian set and a few North Indian sides. While the flavors were definitely decent, the overall experience fell short due to portion sizes and slow service ‚Äî especially considering the price point.

üçΩ What We Ordered:

South Indian Set (Dosa, Idli, Vada with chutneys + sambar)

Malai Kofta

Mushroom Coconut Pepper Fry

Naan Basket

---

üåø South Indian Set

The dosa was crisp, idli soft, and vada decent ‚Äî classic Nalan style. But the chutneys were barely enough to cover even half the dosa, let alone three different items. Looked like they were rationing chutney by the teaspoon. We asked twice for extra chutney, and only on the third attempt did the server bring a tiny refill. The sambar was flavorful but also on the lower side in quantity.

---

üçõ North Indian Dishes

The Malai Kofta tasted great, but the serving had just two koftas drowning in a bowl full of gravy. Not ideal when you‚Äôre sharing. We had to order an extra sabji (Mushroom Coconut Pepper Fry) to make up for it, which took a long time to arrive.

The Naan Basket was also underwhelming. For something that‚Äôs supposed to be shared between two people, the amount of naan was surprisingly little. Definitely not enough carbs to go around with two mains.

---

üßë‚Äçüç≥ Service & Price

The biggest downside was the slow service. Despite a half-full restaurant, we had to repeat ourselves multiple times to get basic things like chutney and extra plates. That dragged out the lunch longer than it needed to be.

For the price, we expected better quantity or at least quicker service. The pricing is on par with larger restaurants in Singapore, but the portions feel like a third of what you‚Äôd get elsewhere.

---

üìù Final Verdict

‚úÖ Taste: On point for most dishes

‚ùå Quantity: Too small across the board

‚ùå Service: Slow and inattentive

‚ùå Value: Price doesn't match the experience

If you're visiting, expect good flavors but come with low expectations on quantity and some patience for service. Probably a better fit for solo diners or small bites, not ideal for group lunches unless you're willing to order (and wait for) more.

Fml the price increase like no tomorrow. Inflation rate 10%‚Ä¶ few years ago, it was $4.5 for small bowl, now it‚Äôs $4.9. The staffs here are also not very generous with their portion. Lunch time queue waiting time can get up to 30mins. Take ‚Ä¶

business_name: Red Lantern Live Seafood @ 921 Upper Bukit Timah Road
text: Came for early CNY reunion with friends.   Average food nothing outstanding.  The Yu Sheng was below average,  too dry and tasteless, and the prawn was dissapointing, not fresh.

Decided to try after reading some blogger who wrote about this place. There wasn't really a menu and the staff just verbally told what was available and basically we ordered each of everything. Service was a little slow even though there were only 6 people in the entire cafe. 1st was the rojak churro which was quite interesting, the churro was like the youtiao and the rest of the ingredients were wrapped in the rice paper. It tasted good but was kinda deconstructed didn't really know how to go about eating it.
The crab burger and Tofu fries was next. Burger was okay quite enjoyable and so was the Tofu fries with the dip sauce. I guess it was a good combination and the tofu fries would just seem kinda out of place by just ordering ala carte.
Last was the coffee pasta, which I thought was the "disaster" of the entire meal. Kinda hard to appreciate coffee taste on the pasta, which left a bitter aftertaste even after the meal. On the other hand the beef that went along with the pasta was so well cooked the meat was very tender and juicy. I think it was cooked separately and later added to the pasta before serving so it didn't really have much of the coffee taste (which I said thank God).

business_name: Dim Sum Express (Kuai Can Dian Xin)
text:
Dim Sum Express (Kuai Can Dian Xin): A Late-Night Dim Sum Haven with Budget-Friendly Bites

Alright, folks, listen up! My friends and I were craving a late-night dim sum fix after an our bike ride, and we stumbled upon Dim Sum Express (Kuai Can Dian Xin). This place was tucked away in a quiet corner, a little off the beaten path, but it was open 24 hours, which was perfect for our late-night cravings.

The Good:

‚Ä¢ The Price: The dim sum was incredibly affordable. They had a deal where you could get a free basket of dim sum for every 10 baskets you bought, making it incredibly budget-friendly.  That was a huge plus, especially when compared to other dim sum places where a similar amount could easily cost you double or even triple the price.

‚Ä¢ The Convenience: It was the perfect spot for a quick and easy meal, especially if you're looking for something budget-friendly. It was open 24 hours, which was a major plus for us!  It was the perfect place to satisfy a late-night craving. Plus, there was a large car park nearby, making parking a breeze.

The Quirks:

‚Ä¢ The Food: The dim sum menu had a lot of variety, but honestly, the taste was just average. The har gow and siu mai, classic dim sum dishes, didn't really wow us.

‚Ä¢ The Coffee Shop: The drink stall next to the dim sum stall only accepted cash, so keep that in mind.

My Friend‚Äôs Note: I love that it‚Äôs open 24 hours! It‚Äôs great to have a place I can go to for dim sum whenever I want!

My Note: The price is great, but I think the food could be better.

Rating:

‚Ä¢ Food: 3/5 (Just okay, not the best dim sum)

‚Ä¢ Service: 3.5/5 (Acceptable)

‚Ä¢ Atmosphere: 3.5/5 (Okay ambience)

Overall: 3/5

Overall: The ambience was decent, and the service was fine, but it was the affordability and the 24-hour availability that really stood out. It‚Äôs a good option for a quick and easy meal, especially if you're looking for something budget-friendly.  I'd say if you're in the area, it's worth popping in to give it a try, but if you're a serious dim sum connoisseur, you might want to check out other options.  But for the price, it‚Äôs a decent choice.
Edited 3 years ago

Definitely must have the prawn paste chicken as a side. The sour sweet pork was also good but I prefer the onions to be more crispy and raw (on a good note, this means no raw onion breath).

Beehoon fish soup too fishy for me despite coming with the knowledge from the other reviews. Managed to finish the ingredients but couldn't drink 95% of the soup, would recommend them to add ginger to broth/soup remove fishy smell and it also acts complimentary to the dish.

Lastly, the Sliced Fish Hor Fun is a bit too charred and doesn't blend well with the tasteless kway two, don't eat it after or before u eat the fish bee hoon, it will shock your taste buds, making the food feel intolerable to even continue eating. It can pair slightly better with the sweet and sour pork. They also only serve traditional tea/water and don't have kopi or teh options.

Toilet is unbearable even if I just wash hands there, so do bring tissues and visit toilet before going there. The setting was okay, became quite loud for a while because of big group gatherings at the back. Queue time longer during the start of lunch hour, came there earlier and thankfully managed to get seats after ten minutes.

Do note that you need to walk quite a bit as it sits in the middle a row of houses. I came here because I heard it was closing in Sep. Is it worth it? I guess for a 1-time visiting in a old brand restaurant with past history where it won't exist after, sure just go eat don't expect anything and it'll be fine.

Came here to celebrate my wife's birthday, with high expectations, given the awesome reviews. First impression was good - ambience was bright and spacious, with high ceilings and classy decor. Service was attentive, but I felt it was a bit impersonal and lacked a certain warmth. Nevertheless, we got everything we needed, and staff did all the necessary for a fine dining restaurant such as pulling our seats back and forward as we sat down. So far, so good. We ordered 2 executive set lunches, and I opted to top up $18 for the Wagyu rump. We selected the carpaccio and truffle mushroom soup for starters. The carpaccio was very thinly sliced and not bad, but the mushroom soup lacked oomph, and I couldn't taste much truffle. I've had heartier mushroom soups at buffet lines, so not a good start food wise. For the mains, we had the farro risotto, and I got the Wagyu rump...which was quite a mistake because despite paying an extra $18, I got a slab of beef that was perhaps 150 to 180g tops, which I couldn't tell was Wagyu, as it lacked any discernible marbling, and was even a tad powdery. My wife enjoyed her risotto much more, but I wasn't a fan either. By then I was quite disappointed with the food, and the dessert didn't do much to redeem the meal. The entire meal came up to be about $150, and for that price, I could go to many places for a better meal - perhaps not as good as ambience nor service, but to me, food quality is the most important metric.

business_name: Siam Square Mookata - Best Mookata Restaurant in Singapore
text: All staff very friendly EXCEPT the aunty. Grumpy, black face, and always angry ( dont know who offended her). Food wise ok, not bad. A variety of sauce mixture for you to choose.

business_name: Crystal Jade La Mian Xiao Long Bao
text:
My family and I used to frequent Crystal Jade for their noodles with minced meat & mushroom. Came again in June 2025 and to our disappointment, this dish is no longer on the menu.

The menu has been updated for what is currently popular - mala, sour fish, etc which I personally think is not a very smart move. If I wanted to eat mala & sour fish, I would head to a China chain where they are established experts on that flavour profile.

Nevertheless, we tried the sour fish la mian. It's okay. It's not bad but it's not good either - fish is dry, although soup is flavourful and spicy.

Thankfully their dim sum has remained the same, quality and enjoyable although not the best out there. The dishes were served very quickly, although it took us almost 15 minutes to get seated when there were several empty tables.

The staff are pretty good and are trying their best, but the truth is this place is understaffed and you can feel it. Thankfully the kitchen doesn't seem to be understaffed.

After their menu revamp, the best part of this Crystal Jade outlet is the atmosphere and the place. It is comfortable, spacious and neither too bright nor dim. It will be a good choice for dim sum & if you are not too hungry.

business_name: Ristorante Takada : Japanese Italian restaurant : Pasta Pizza Wine (Alexandra)
text: Came for the Restaurant Week 4-course dinner menu. Good quality is good, uni pasta with squid ink was my favorite, beef cheek was up to the standard. However, the services was disappointing... apparently there was a new staff and they are ‚Ä¶

Nice place to chill with kids in tow. Kept them occupied with finger food while we watched soccer! Interesting selection of pizza, including bak kwa pizza. We enjoyed our Goat's Lager and the cheesy fries with bacon bits were wiped off fairly quickly.
The portion is generous‚Äîan army stew could easily feed three people. Side dishes are self-service and unlimited, with free water provided. ‚Ä¶
The place was well decorated. Some menu items were not available, and the food tasted just ok. This was not my first time here. ‚Ä¶

Been to this outlet several times since I move nearby in Aug 23. Visited today for dine-in 31 Dec 23 and discovered prices have went up a bit with the change of menu. Some good items such as Penny with Crispy Chicken, Chilly Crab Pasta are no longer available. Choices are lesser and no longer economical as before.

1) Chicken Chop is dry and hard, fries were cold.
2) Fish and Chips portion shrink
3) Truffle Mushroom paste creamy and good taste
4) Bacon Penny was good too

TL;DR

Despite the commendable service, it was the ambience that fell short of expectations for a premium dining experience, particularly considering prices potentially exceeding $1,000, which presents a challenge in justifying a return visit.

Full review-

Ambience:

Upon arrival, the open layout of the restaurant was unexpected, deviating from the anticipated intimate atmosphere characteristic of high-end dining establishments. The proximity of larger tables the could fit 4 or more led to a noisy environment, detracting from the overall dining experience.

Notably during my service, the noise level was such that the service staff had to speak louder to ensure I could hear their introductions of the dishes.

The absence of private rooms, if any, was conspicuous, leaving patrons without the option of a more secluded setting.

Food/drinks:

While the presentation of each dish was meticulous and visually appealing, some fell short in terms of flavour complexity. Notably, the fish dish lacked seasoning, resulting in a rather bland taste profile despite the accompanying sauce.

Service:

On a positive note, the service provided was exemplary, with staff demonstrating attentiveness and a genuine commitment to customer satisfaction.

Their willingness to accommodate dietary preferences and offer detailed explanations of each dish added to the overall dining experience, mitigating some of the shortcomings in other areas.

Would I return?

Given the disparity between the anticipated upscale ambience and the actual dining environment, coupled with the substantial financial investment required, I find myself hesitant to consider a return visit.

business_name: Jing Jing Hokkien Mee & Oyster Omelette
text:
Black was sweet. Crisp and soft.
White was plain. Cai poh not enough to cover it up.
Price is nice for the food. Sambal soso.

We visit this restaurant whenever we have celebrations. We tried carbonara pasta, aglio olio, truffle pizza, salad, truffle fries and creme brulee. Pretty decent Italian food or maybe I haven't had the opportunity to visit Italy to try the ‚Ä¶

business_name: The Halia at Singapore Botanic Gardens
text: The jug of iced lemon tea was a lovely relief after a long hot walk in the Botanical Garden. The view of the bird outside the window was amazing! However, the cashier tried to overcharge us double for the drink! The price stated in the menu was SG10, but he quoted SG24, including tax as he said it was for a big jug! We refused to pay SG24 as there was no ‚Äúbig‚Äù jug stated in the menu! Finally, we paid SG12, including tax! üôÑüò¨üò° In spite of that unfortunate incident, we still find the Orchid Garden one of the best!

Went there for family gathering but I guess they are overwhelmed thus service & food wise not really up to standard. When ordered set, shld be 2-3 dishes first but it keeps on coming in & filled up the whole table.  Food not according to what we've request in terms of sequence so not very impressed with it. Before i start my meal,  the cutlery are not cleaned too cos the stain still can be seen,  quite disappointed overall.

The view is scenic, food is ok but lots of improvement in terms of service. The waitress wasn't approachable probably she's too busy, the waiter did not bother to respond when queried. However, do look out for the waiter in polo shirt, Raja. He is probably the only one who is friendly & approachable, and the only reason for you to be back again.
Food is Good n price is fair.....

Food was normal to be, there are much nicer pastas out there imo‚Ä¶
Pizza was great but salty, thinly made with crispy crust.
The meat ball appetiser was my favourite.
The air con was blowing directly and the food got cold really fast.

Egg Prata n Plain Prata is nice. The taste of Maggie goreng is not something we like. Just felt the coin Prata should add more butter. Remember to ask for less sweet Teh Tarik and less sweet coffee if u dun like too sweet drink.
Thanks for the wrong drink after additional price added and paid for ice milo

Ppl are playing loud noise at the coffee shop while we were enjoying our dinner. In the afternoon, there are pigeons flying around....it is really disturbing. But the shop helpers will try to chase them away. I will really hope to stop ‚Ä¶

Popular place for a late night snack or dinner. Reasonably priced. Seating inside is limited. However seating outside by the road is more popular. Crowded with youngsters. Opens around 6 pm until late next morning. Decent quality. One of the few overnight restaurants around this part of town

business_name: Legendary Classics by Legendary Hong Kong
text:
Unfortunately none of the dim sums we had was up to our expectations coming from two Hong Kongers.

Prawn dumplings were acceptable but could use more seasoning and bigger filling if the claim is ‚Äúauthentic‚Äù. Siew mais were acceptable also but under seasoned to say the least. Rice rolls were okay but the fillings could be more and finely minced.

Generous portion of the turnip cakes but the flour was overly pressed so it was quite poorly made. And the sesame paste buns were simply unacceptable with overly thick and dry skin and fillings were just too solid not enough oil and grind. (I left 70% of the buns untouched)

Nice ambience and nice service but as far as dim sums are concerned this is unlikely to be getting a repeat visit from us any time soon.

The udon texture is good, smooth and chewy. Soup is a dashi with pork, like that they provide a bowl of tempura crumbs at the side for customers to add to their udon, it gives a nice texture contrast to the slurpy udon. Added prawn and enoki mushroom tempura but they were cold, it would be better if they are freshly prepared. The presentation of the food can be improved too.

2nd visit here, bit of a disappointment from last visit. Food was great but charges on tea offered is not upfront. Hate it when restaurants don‚Äôt disclaim it when teas cost you $30 a pop. Only thing that kept this from going to a 3 star review was Jason‚Äôs lovely service through the night. Was a confusing serve when sommelier paired a red wine for our chicken main? Skip the pairing and tea though, nothing phenomenal here. Don‚Äôt think I‚Äôll be back for a third.

Just another usual Western Food place. Food taste are just normal and average, nothing to wow. Food portion normal. Service is average as well. Beer options are V V limited (dissapointing). If you are a beer person pls give this place a miss.

Very limited seats inside air-con area, so for big groups you are expected to sit outdoor, it is sheltered but not meant for bad weather. Do expect crowd during meal time though.

Carpark is available at nearby MSCP. Washroom available on site.

Service can be real slow due to low manpower. Though staffs are friendly but also stressed up, from my observation, notice there are just 2 staffs running the whole place (to serve and man the cashier/takeaway/dine in/food delivery orders). ‚Ä¶

Was excited to spot this stall. It had been quite some time since gaving trishaw noodles. Their braised wings & curry fishball & radish were so yummy. Maybe chose the wrong noodle type as in thin in size. Should have ask for instant noodles instead. Both the sauces were being added in, very tasty
I felt that the char-grill chicken was quite tender and juicy. Fried fish was rather commonplace standard.

2 of us - We ordered Hainanese Pork Chop and Egg Plant Mushroom Cheese which we had eaten before and these 2 dishes was nice and within expectation. I remembered that their Fried Nai Bai is also nice. ‚Ä¶

Overall food taste: 3.5/5‚≠êÔ∏è Finally dropped by to dine in at this place after seeing some previous good reviews! I had the fish & chips - a menu item I was looking forward to try after coming across those few positive reviews. I liked that ‚Ä¶
The prata and curry is normal , nothing fanastic
Dosa was good . Prata and fish curry also yummy.standard hawker centr service and ambience
2 years ago

A nice place to lunch if you are averse to crowds on a weekday. The view overlooking the backyard was fantastic during the storm, made one feel cosy indoors. Food wise, some vegan options, interesting menu but nothing really yelled out ‚Äòi‚Äôm awesome‚Äô! the flat white was good.

As the only access is via stairs, have to rule out this place for those who need the lift. The ladies had beautiful wallpaper but was too dimly lit.
Located at basement 1 of Lot One, alight at Choa Chu Kang of the North South Red Line and take a escalator down. ‚Ä¶
We went there for lunch, and was a bit disappointed that the lunch menu was quite limited, compared to the full dinner menu. ‚Ä¶

Good place to have Indian food at a reasonable price. Plenty of veg and Non Veg options to select from. Need some improvement on the dal khichadi though. Also service was a bit slow. But overall it was a good experience.

Thunder tea rice. This is the name of the dish that is sold at this stall.
It‚Äôs a Hakka speciality of healthy grain bowl, where you can choose white/ brown rice that‚Äôs topped with a variety of stir fried cut vegetables of spinach, cabbage and long beans. They also added cut fried tofu. Mix them all up and tuck in.
They also serve side of aromatic herb ‚Äòsoup‚Äô made from basil, mint and grounded nuts.
You can have add-one such as fried yong tau foo pieces and fried omelette to your meal.
And they also have got a Michelin Bib Gourmand award too!
Recommended!

Visited on 26 January 2025 and had an overall pleasant dining experience. Most of the dishes were well-executed, but the seafood fried rice was drier than expected due to an excessive amount of fried rice crisps, which overpowered the dish. ‚Ä¶
Service was amazing. Recommend the scallop appetiser. Portion was on the small side

October 2024
Good selection of craft beers. Different price at different time of the day under current promotion. Food not bad either. Great venue for social gatherings. Not expensive and good service.

Quite a relaxing place to dine in at night.

Food is not bad.

Pretty value for money set lunch, loved every dish that was served; octopus, the pork jowl, the snapper w eggplants & green curry, the parsnip licorice dessert. There‚Äôs great balance of Southeast Asian flavors with a contemporary approach, and decent prices while not being too expensive.
Second visit for dinner, I thought that many of the dishes were executed really well, with surprisingly good ones being the brik pastry, the chimichurri on the pork ribeye and the lamb glaze.
Service does have room for improvement especially with training the newer staff though it won‚Äôt hinder me from another visit.

Average lunch crowds. Great excellent service officers. Very Polite and professional. Nice ambience. Food kind of slightly above average. Roasted Pork rib were little dry. Had it been more tender and juices will be marvelous. Really enjoyed very fries

Fresh crab- must try

Steam fish not so fresh[ apply to us only , exp base on hotpot fresh fish] ‚Ä¶

The ambiance is warm and inviting, with cozy seating, large glass windows, and intimate tables. Service was excellent. As for the food, I found it average, I tried the braised beef cheek and the Iberico pork. That said, it's a fantastic spot for good conversation. Would I return? Definitely, though I‚Äôd go for different dishes next time to give it another shot.

Thick, starchy & tasty.
The fish maw soup with crab ü¶Ä meat , is a great alternative to shark‚Äôs fin soup and suitably collagen-rich too! üòÅ
This bowl has chock-full of fish maw strips, crab meat and fluffy egg drop. Add-on splashes of black vinegar for an extra punch of flavour! üòã

Had dinner last night at the restaurant.  We have Cantabarian Anchovies, traditional French onion soup, sauteed frog legs, fries and rillete as appetizers.  Have peppercrusted ribeye and "claypot chicken" as main.  Meal, wine and service are good.  very lively ambience on Tuesday night, tells you that they are popular.  For dessert, we ordered profiteroles, black forest cake, and melted chocolate.  Our group very much enjoyed the profiteroles.  We brought 1 wine and bought 2 bottles.  Corkerage is $50 but you buy one get one free.

My first time trying Greek food and it was very tasty. I particularly liked the pita bread and hummus. But this is not uniquely Greek. Still I enjoyed the food here. The eggplant was a little bitter and really needed the feta cheese to ‚Ä¶
Tasty fresh reasonable price of Sushi bento!
Very traditional Lui Cha, not too salty. Like their Tea.. mix it with rice and its heavenly!!

A popular BKT shop who has been operating around for a while.

It is the standard clear BKT soup with peppery taste, goes well with the sweet ‚Ä¶

Had the tsukemen. Overly salty and lack of flavour from the dipping broth/sauce.

The chicken karaage is delicious! And there‚Äôs free flow beansprouts.

Air conditioning is bad and the place feels hot.

Service was ok.

Tasty foods with reasonable price. Their signature roasted duck meat was tender. Its skin was crispy. They offer a lot of veg dishes too.
They serve canned tiger beer.
Some staff could communicate only in Chinese.

I have been visiting this place for the past 20 years since my parents would bring me here for lunch/dinner after a swim.
Honestly I feel that the standard of food hasn't changed much over these years ‚Ä¶
Good vibe.  Wonderful service from the students. great presentation.

Located along Clementi Road towards west coast highway, this restaurant was highly visible and a public car park was nearby for those who drive. The food were priced competitively and a reasonably big place with round tables. Ordered some ‚Ä¶

Came for a birthday celebration in mid Dec 2023. Since it was a 2 star establishment, I was quite hyped about the visit. We had the tasting menu and got the prestige pairing plus I brought a bottle of Iwa 5 Assemblage 3.

The food didn't really wow me until we got to the proteins. It was really a lacklustre start. The beverage pairing was really interesting though and it was no surprise why that cost more than the food.

All in all, a decent experience but not something memorable.

It was our first time dining there for lunch. Service offered & the food quality were great! We ordered the Premium Buta Bara Don (Pork Belly Ricebowl), Iberico Hoho Don (Pork Jowl Ricebowl) - both with Onsen Tamago, Jumbo Kaki Fry (Fried ‚Ä¶

Apr 2019. I loved the food here. We ordered Kailan, spinach, sambal fish and chicken curry.
Everything was so deliciously done and tasted home-cooked.
Other than the nice food, i saw a harmonious working culture here. The younger Malay staff could speak Mandarin and were respectful to an elderly Chinese auntie.
Lots of positive energy. üëçüëçüëçüëçüëç

The atmosphere and service were excellent, very nostalgic and cozy. However, some of the food was not as high quality as I would have expected for the price point. The shashlik beef was extremely tough, likely due to the cut of meat used, ‚Ä¶

business_name: Boon Lay Traditional Hakka Lui Cha
text: Varies vegetables like cabbage, long bean amd some nuts on rice with a bowl of strong veg soup. All at 3.50sgd and filling even for a big guy like me.

Seems much of the dishes are more akin to home-cooked Burmese version of Economic Rice (veggies and meat combi), although the usual iconic menus like Mohinga (bee hoon soup), Burmese briyani, and Lahpet Thoke (fermented tea leaves salad) also make appearances. There's always Burmese customers lining up to buy meals during dinner time, so you know what they serve are authentic.

The Burmese economic rice was relatively well-priced for such a cuisine that is foreign to local Singaporeans (like $4-5), thus making it popular among Burmese diaspora in the area. Tastes stronger than other Southeast Asian cuisines - you can tell there's rather substantial Indian (Bengali) influences in it. Their mohinga was served in pretty large portion with thick soup. Greatly appreciate their effort in providing two separate takeout containers for the soup and filling (bee hoon, meat, egg, bits of fritters, chili flakes, coriander, and piece of lemon)!
5 years ago
The steak was perfect, very very well cooked. Weekend wine promo is also very sweet, as the price at their wine shop is very decent. Overall a nice place to chill over weekends.

The food was pretty good, was happily surprised by the ragu pasta that had the right level of cooking (quite rare in Singapore). My friend thought the place was a bit noisy, service was ok overall.

Quite expensive if you are really hungry but hey it's Singapore and the quality is there.

Mee Siam nice
Boss nice, once monthly do charity give out food free vegetarian bee hoon set to promote vegetarian

Had their Black Garlic Ramen @ LeQuest. Surprisingly good ramen in such a hidden spot. The star is undoubtedly the soup base - thick and savory without being too oily. The noodles were firm and had bite. Chashu was small but tasty. Ajitama was well seasoned and soft in centre. I like their extras - free flow of barley tea and bean sprouts and even wet wipes.
Ate prata, roti john and maggie soup. All three are delicious. Love the athmosphere. Chill. Not so crowded. They have nice sofa seats with high back rest, like those in old American restaurants.

When I see the word ‚Äúsignature‚Äù on the menu, I knew I had to try their Signature vermicelli bowl set (ùòâùò∂ùòØ ùòµùò©ùò™ùòµ ùòØùò∂ùò∞ùòØùò® ùò§ùò©ùò¢ ùò®ùò™ùò∞ ùòµùò∞ùòÆ)! A filling bowl of noodles with grilled pork, fried spring roll & fresh vegetables, the set also includes ‚Ä¶

Friends hosted dinner here and the food was really good.

We had the roast chicken, which was full of flavour and the skin was crispy, though one or two pieces of meat were a little dry.  The mixed roast meats platter was also good, consisting of crispy skin pork, duck and jelly.

The tofu with seaweed was also a hit, but the evening‚Äôs best dish was the noodles, which was full of wok hei. The prawns with pumpkin were also super tasty.  The sweet and sour soup was filled with ingredients as well.

Service was warm and friendly.   You need someone who is a member of NUSS to invite you.

it was quiet on the weekday evening we came by. loved how tender the pork chops were, even though they were deep fried. but the black curry beef looked non-appetising though, even though it tasted alright. do grind the sesame & mix it in with the sauce for extra flavour. loved their sesame sauce dressing for their free flow salad too! üòã

Baked rice was good. Small portion but means space is kept for dessert. Cheese if more burnt will be good. Son had fried chicken. Looks good as well as he wants all 3 for himself. Ice cream as expected is good. Pricey during normal times but hey, it's my birthday month. Service here is fast and responsive. Late lunch at 3pm so more time for everything. Remember, get the membership. It's cheaper on the birthday month and you can get a free sundae.
